        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "Higher Education",
          "Not Applicable",
          "To X% GPA",
          "Excellent vs Good vs Poor",
          "8228 students",
          "Not Applicable",
          "Web Browsing, Consumption Data, Library, Gateway Logins, Student Demographics",
          "[Sequences of Logs, OHE vectors of static data]",
          "First 2 weeks",
          "For target, the authors discretize GPA into a multiclass problem where the top X% (X=5, 10, 15, 20) are Excellent, the bottom X% are poor and all students in the middle become considered as good. \n\nFor every feature, authors select different levels of aggregation - 4 hours for web page browsing. In others, aggregation was daily.\n\nRecords with same data, time and place were merged.\n\nStatic data is converted into a OHE vector .\n\nDepending on the source, data is either interpreted by an LSTM module or a 2DCNN.\n\nClass imbalance addressed with weighted loss function instead of the common cross-entropy.\n\nA way to augment the data was to divide the chunks of 145 days from the sample into 10 pieces and consider each piece as a new sample → with the same label as the original student. ",
          "Logistic Regression, CART, AdaBoost, Random Forest, DO. V, Do.T, ",
          "Holdout Method",
          "20% threshold\n\n{Accuracy: 0.83 - Do. T, Macro Precision: 0.85- Do. T, Macro Recall: 0.78 - Do. T, Macro F1-Score: 0.80 - Do. T}",
          "Authors use a different approach than most other works. In this case, they use campus data - card data essentially, to predict GPA. Logs are not only LMS logs, but rather logs collected from the entire institution. \n\nResults shown only consider the target definition as having 20% of the data. Reason being that the limits between classes are not as strict. ",
          "Oversampling via chunking a sequence would only be ideal if the behaviour every 2 weeks was consistent. \n\nHoldout Method\n\nHard to Replicate for other institutions\n\nDoes not consider data related with learner interactions with course materials"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
  ],
